    <figure xml:id="fig-IQsampa">
    <caption>
    An illustration of the how sampling distribution of the mean depends on sample size. I generated
    10,000 samples of IQ data, and calculated the mean IQ observed within each of
    these data sets. The histogram shows the distribution of these means (i.e., the sampling
    distribution of the mean). The individual IQ score was drawn from a normal distribution with mean 100
    and standard deviation 15, which is shown as the solid black line). In this plot, each data set contained
    only a single observation, so the mean of each sample is just one person's IQ score. As a consequence,
    the sampling distribution of the mean is of course identical to the population distribution of IQ scores.
    <xref ref="fig-IQsampb"/> illustrates when the sample size at 2, and <xref ref="fig-IQsampc"/> for a sample size of 10.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/IQsampa.png"/>
    </figure>
